{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513052"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11995"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11995"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.18,0.02,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65854"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44369"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a two day history of a painful right knee and chills. She had recently recovered from a viral illness after arriving back from interstate travel during which she had multiple mosquitoes bites. She has not developed any rash nor had any recent trauma. Her medical conditions include osteoarthritis in her knees, hypertension and scoliosis. She has not had any recent surgery. Her medications include paracetamol, perindopril, amlodipine and hydrochlorothiazide. She has a blood pressure of 100/80 mmHg, pulse 105/min and temperature 38.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her right knee is hot, tender and swollen, with a severely restricted range of movement. On bloods, there is leucocytosis of 14 x10\u003Csup\u003E^\u003C/sup\u003E9/L (RR 4-11) and an elevated C-reactive protein of 85 (RR 0-5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic arthritis","Ross river virus associated arthritis","Acute gout flare","Reactive arthritis","Deep vein thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be suspected in patients presenting with a painful, hot and swollen joint associated with fevers and the inability to weight bear. It is usually monoarticular and commonly affects the hip or knee. Leucocytes and inflammatory markers are elevated and synovial fluid analysis is performed to confirm the diagnosis. Blood cultures should also be taken to rule out bacteraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoss river virus\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection that spreads to humans via mosquito bites and is one of the most common mosquito-borne infections in Australia. Majority of people have no symptoms but a minority will develop symptoms usually within 21 days of infection including polyarthritis, truncal rash, malaise, myalgia and fevers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGout\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis a type of crystal arthropathy and is commonly caused by hyperuricaemia. Under polarizing microscopy, synovial fluid analysis reveals needle-shaped, negatively birefringent crystals. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute gout flare\u003C/strong\u003E is a common mimicker of septic arthritis. Common triggers include dehydration, diuretics, and alcohol usage. However, given the fevers, markedly raised CRP and WCC pointing towards an infective cause, septic arthritis has to be ruled out initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inflammatory arthritis usually caused by gastrointestinal or urinary tract infections. The classic triad of symptoms consists of arthritis, urethritis and conjunctivitis. Though the patient has recently recovered from an unknown viral illness, given the severity of the presentation, septic arthritis has to be ruled out in the first instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be suspected in patients with painful, unilateral limb swelling with risk factors including recent surgery, pregnancy, malignancy and prolonged periods of immobilisation. Thrombi are usually found in the lower limbs (such as the calves) and not in joint spaces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acute onset of monoarticular pain, erythema, warmth and significantly reduced mobility should raise suspicion of septic arthritis. Prompt diagnosis and treatment can significantly reduce morbidity and mortality.","Synovial fluid analysis is crucial in differentiating septic arthritis from other causes of joint inflammation.","Septic arthritis is a medical emergency that requires urgent intervention to prevent joint destruction and systemic complications."],"references":["Momodu II, Savaliya V. Septic Arthritis. [Updated 2022 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538176/","Fenando A, Rednam M, Gujarathi R, et al. Gout. [Updated 2022 May 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546606/","Earwood JS, Walker TR, Sue GJC. Septic Arthritis: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Dec 1;104(6):589-597. PMID: 34913662. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34913662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65854"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11995"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65854"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T16:40:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T16:42:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80563"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"E